HeLa cells were selected as a model cell line to further demonstrate the usability for intracellular sensing.[9,17,31,63] First, the N-CDs and HeLa cells were incubated for various incubation times (1 h, 6 h, 12 h, and 24 h) at 37 °C in a medium.[1,11,38,54,61] As illustrated in Fig. 6
                        , there was no obvious fluorescence enhancement when cells were co-incubated with N-CDs for 1 h, and the fluorescence intensity in the cells gradually became stronger as the incubation time increased to 24 h.[17,29,30,32,51] The cells displayed a bright blue fluorescence and remained the complete morphology, which demonstrated that these N-CDs favorably crossed the cell membrane to enter the cells through endocytosis.[41,43,49,62,67] Meanwhile, the optimal concentration of N-CDs was 100 μg∙mL−1 according to Fig. S11. Subsequently, various concentrations of exogenous CAL were introduced into HeLa cells pretreated with N-CDs to further explore the semi-quantitative monitoring of intracellular CAL levels.[11,43,59,68] The fluorescence intensity of N-CDs was greatly quenched within 10 min when CAL increased to 300 μM (Fig. 7
                        ). Then, 100 μM of l-Arg/l-Lys and N-CDs-CAL system were co-incubated for 20 min and significant fluorescence recovery was observed. These results demonstrated that the N-CDs as a promising fluorescent probe could be employed to monitor CAL and l-Arg/l-Lys in vivo and in vitro.[14,36,38,47,69].
